(30, 'baby_development', 'any', 'any', null, 'Physical confidence keeps growing - many toddlers run, jump with both feet, kick a ball, and climb eagerly. Stair and balance skills vary; keep an adult close, use a rail or hand when needed, and supervise play equipment carefully.', 0),
(30, 'baby_development', 'any', 'any', null, 'Language often becomes more useful for everyday needs - some toddlers use short phrases or sentences, name actions in pictures, and may begin asking "what" or "where" questions. Clarity and range still vary widely, especially in multilingual homes.', 1),
(30, 'baby_development', 'any', 'any', null, 'Early concepts grow through ordinary play: count body parts or stairs, compare big and small, name colours, and follow familiar routines. Keep these as enjoyable invitations, not skills to test or teach with special toys.', 2),
(30, 'baby_development', 'any', 'any', null, 'Pretend play may grow more imaginative and social - inviting you into a game, giving a toy a "voice," or acting out a familiar routine. Join in, follow toddler''s lead, and model simple turn-taking and kind words.', 3),
(30, 'baby_development', 'any', 'any', null, 'If your child was born significantly early, ask your paediatrician how to interpret milestones for them. Raise any loss of skills, a specific concern, or a question about communication or development promptly.', 4),
(30, 'mum_wellbeing', 'any', 'any', null, 'Big feelings continue through this stretch - the same rhythm helps: name the feeling, hold a short calm limit, offer two safe choices, reconnect once calm returns, and praise small moments of cooperation.', 0),
(30, 'mum_wellbeing', 'any', 'any', null, 'Seek support from your doctor or a trusted person if low mood, anxiety, anger, hopelessness, sleep trouble beyond toddler-related waking, or feeling unable to cope is lasting or worsening. Urgent help is needed if you feel unsafe or have thoughts of harming yourself or someone else.', 1),
(30, 'mum_wellbeing', 'any', 'any', null, 'Rest, shared care, and small moments for yourself remain valid priorities. Asking for help is part of caring for your family, not a failure to manage.', 2),
(30, 'buy_now', 'any', 'any', null, 'Offer 3-4 varied family meals and 1-2 nutritious snacks according to appetite. Include iron-rich foods such as dals/beans, eggs, meat/fish where eaten, and leafy vegetables; offer water with and between meals; and continue breastfeeding if you both wish. Cow''s milk or dairy can be part of the diet, but should not crowd out meals. Encourage, but do not force, eating.', 0),
(30, 'buy_now', 'any', 'any', null, 'There is no need to buy special learning toys. Picture books, crayons, simple puzzles, large blocks, pretend-play props, and everyday counting during meals, stairs, or tidying are plenty. Choose sturdy, age-appropriate items without small detachable parts.', 1),
(30, 'buy_now', 'any', 'any', null, 'For winter, choose warm, breathable layers that allow free movement. Keep indoor play active, add or remove a layer as needed, and change sweaty or damp clothing promptly.', 2),
(30, 'hold_off', 'any', 'any', null, 'Keep food and household-safety boundaries: cut grapes lengthwise; avoid whole nuts, popcorn, hard sweets, and hard raw pieces; lock button batteries, magnets, medicines, cleaners, and small objects away; and supervise eating. If screens are used, keep them brief, adult-supported, and away from meals and bedtime. Follow toilet-training readiness gently, and avoid pressure around speech, counting, or skill timing.', 0),
(30, 'movement_rest', 'any', 'any', null, 'Continue safe active play - running, jumping, climbing, ball play, and supervised stairs. Secure stairs, windows/balconies, furniture, and TVs; keep loose mats, cords, and small objects out of busy walking routes; and avoid seated wheeled walkers.', 0),
(30, 'movement_rest', 'any', 'any', null, 'Shared reading, songs, simple puzzles, pretend play, and ordinary counting or colour talk support thinking and language naturally. Let toddler try small self-help tasks with time and close supervision rather than turning play into a test.', 1),
(30, 'movement_rest', 'any', 'any', null, 'For you: continue whatever movement and rest rhythm feels sustainable. A short walk, stretch, or quiet break can count.', 2),
(30, 'appointments_safety', 'any', 'any', null, 'If your child is up to date, no routine UIP vaccine dose is scheduled this month. Vitamin A continues every six months from 16-18 months until age five; confirm the card and the next due date with your paediatrician or local programme, as private schedules and local services may differ. If the 30-month developmental review has not happened, arrange it and ask for a standardised developmental screening.', 0),
(30, 'appointments_safety', 'any', 'any', null, 'If your toddler is climbing out of the cot, it may be time to plan a low, age-appropriate bed and make the whole room safe: secure furniture, remove climbable hazards, gate stairs if needed, and keep a predictable bedtime routine. There is no fixed transition age. Brush teeth twice daily with a rice-grain smear of fluoride toothpaste and arrange a dental visit if one has not yet happened or if you have concerns.', 1),
(30, 'appointments_safety', 'any', 'any', null, 'Seek urgent care for breathing difficulty, a seizure, unusual difficulty waking, a serious injury, suspected poisoning, or choking. Contact your paediatrician promptly for poor drinking or dehydration, repeated vomiting or diarrhoea, blood in stool, fever that worries you, or a child who seems much less alert than usual.', 2),
(30, 'appointments_safety', 'any', 'winter', null, 'With an active, curious toddler, winter burn prevention matters: keep heaters, hot drinks, hot water, cooking appliances, and cords out of reach; check bathwater before use; and never leave toddler alone near a heat source.', 3),
(30, 'appointments_safety', 'any', 'winter', null, 'Dress in warm, breathable layers and avoid overheating. Moisturise dry skin regularly. If you use a humidifier, choose cool mist, keep it out of reach, and clean it exactly as directed by the manufacturer.', 4),
(30, 'appointments_safety', 'any', 'winter', null, 'During respiratory-virus season, handwashing before meals and after outdoor play still matters. Use reasonable caution with unwell visitors, and ask your paediatrician about fever, breathing trouble, poor drinking, or symptoms that worry you.', 5),
(31, 'baby_development', 'any', 'any', null, 'Physical play keeps growing - a toddler may run and change direction, kick a ball, climb eagerly, or try small jumps. Keep play close to the ground, avoid jumping from heights, and stay nearby on stairs and play equipment.', 0),
(31, 'baby_development', 'any', 'any', null, 'Language often becomes more useful for everyday needs - some toddlers use longer phrases, ask more questions, and are understood well by family. Clarity to others and the length of phrases still vary widely, especially in multilingual homes.', 1),
(31, 'baby_development', 'any', 'any', null, 'Everyday thinking grows through safe problem-solving: stacking, matching, fitting a lid on a child-safe container, completing a large-piece puzzle, or following a familiar two- or three-step routine. Keep it playful, not a skill to test.', 2),
(31, 'baby_development', 'any', 'any', null, 'Pretend play may become more elaborate and social, sometimes copying real-life scenes in detail. Join in, follow toddler''s lead, and use pretend play to practise simple routines, feelings, and turn-taking.', 3),
(31, 'baby_development', 'any', 'any', null, 'If your child was born significantly early, ask your paediatrician how to interpret milestones for them. Raise any loss of skills, a specific concern, or a question about communication or development promptly.', 4),
(31, 'mum_wellbeing', 'any', 'any', null, 'Big feelings continue through this stretch - the same rhythm helps: name the feeling, hold a short calm limit, offer two safe choices, reconnect once calm returns, and praise small moments of cooperation.', 0),
(31, 'mum_wellbeing', 'any', 'any', null, 'Seek support from your doctor or a trusted person if low mood, anxiety, anger, hopelessness, sleep trouble beyond toddler-related waking, or feeling unable to cope is lasting or worsening. Urgent help is needed if you feel unsafe or have thoughts of harming yourself or someone else.', 1),
(31, 'mum_wellbeing', 'any', 'any', null, 'Rest, shared care, and small moments for yourself remain valid priorities. Asking for help is part of caring for your family, not a failure to manage.', 2),
(31, 'buy_now', 'any', 'any', null, 'Offer 3-4 varied family meals and 1-2 nutritious snacks according to appetite. Include iron-rich foods such as dals/beans, eggs, meat/fish where eaten, and leafy vegetables; offer water with and between meals; and continue breastfeeding if you both wish. Cow''s milk or dairy can be part of the diet, but should not crowd out meals. Encourage, but do not force, eating.', 0),
(31, 'buy_now', 'any', 'any', null, 'Everyday materials support learning without special purchases: books, crayons, large blocks, simple puzzles, and adult-checked, unbreakable pretend-play items. Count or name colours during daily routines; avoid objects with small detachable parts, sharp edges, batteries, or access to unsafe cupboards or rooms.', 1),
(31, 'buy_now', 'any', 'any', null, 'For winter, choose warm, breathable layers that allow free movement. Keep indoor play active, add or remove a layer as needed, and change sweaty or damp clothing promptly.', 2),
(31, 'hold_off', 'any', 'any', null, 'Keep food and household-safety boundaries: cut grapes lengthwise; avoid whole nuts, popcorn, hard sweets, and hard raw pieces; lock button batteries, magnets, medicines, cleaners, and small objects away; and supervise eating. If screens are used, keep them to no more than one hour a day of child content with an adult present, away from meals and bedtime. Follow toilet-training readiness gently, and avoid pressure around speech or problem-solving.', 0),
(31, 'movement_rest', 'any', 'any', null, 'Continue safe active play - running, jumping, climbing, ball play, and supervised stairs. Secure furniture, TVs, windows/balconies, and stairs; keep loose mats, cords, and small objects out of busy walking routes; and avoid seated wheeled walkers.', 0),
(31, 'movement_rest', 'any', 'any', null, 'Safe problem-solving play, pretend scenes, picture talk, and everyday concept talk support thinking and language naturally. Let toddler try small self-help tasks with time and close supervision rather than turning play into a test.', 1),
(31, 'movement_rest', 'any', 'any', null, 'For you: continue whatever movement and rest rhythm feels sustainable. A short walk, stretch, or quiet break can count.', 2),
(31, 'appointments_safety', 'any', 'any', null, 'If your child is up to date, no routine UIP vaccine dose is scheduled this month. Vitamin A continues every six months from 16-18 months until age five; confirm the card and the next due date with your paediatrician or local programme, as private schedules and local services may differ. If the 30-month developmental review has not happened, arrange it and ask for a standardised developmental screening.', 0),
(31, 'appointments_safety', 'any', 'any', null, 'If your toddler is climbing out of the cot, it may be time to plan a low, age-appropriate bed and make the whole room safe: secure furniture, remove climbable hazards, gate stairs if needed, and keep a predictable bedtime routine. There is no fixed transition age. Brush teeth twice daily with a rice-grain smear of fluoride toothpaste and arrange a dental visit if one has not yet happened or if you have concerns.', 1),
(31, 'appointments_safety', 'any', 'any', null, 'Seek urgent care for breathing difficulty, a seizure, unusual difficulty waking, a serious injury, suspected poisoning, or choking. Contact your paediatrician promptly for poor drinking or dehydration, repeated vomiting or diarrhoea, blood in stool, fever that worries you, or a child who seems much less alert than usual.', 2),
(31, 'appointments_safety', 'any', 'winter', null, 'If respiratory illnesses are circulating locally, watch for breathing difficulty, fast or laboured breathing, poor drinking, unusual sleepiness, or symptoms that are worsening. These need prompt medical advice rather than routine home care.', 3),
(31, 'appointments_safety', 'any', 'winter', null, 'Keep the home and car completely smoke-free: opening windows, fans, or ventilation do not make indoor smoking safe. Reduce toddler exposure to cooking and heating smoke where possible, and keep child away from fuel-burning appliances.', 4),
(31, 'appointments_safety', 'any', 'winter', null, 'Winter burn and dry-air safety still matters: keep heaters, hot drinks, hot water, cooking appliances, and cords out of reach; check bathwater; dress in warm layers without overheating; and use a cool-mist humidifier only if kept out of reach and cleaned as directed.', 5),
(32, 'baby_development', 'any', 'any', null, 'Physical confidence keeps growing - a toddler may run smoothly, change direction, climb low playground equipment, kick a ball, or propel a ride-on toy with their feet. Wide variation remains normal, and close supervision is still needed.', 0),
(32, 'baby_development', 'any', 'any', null, 'Language and social communication keep growing - a toddler may use short back-and-forth exchanges, ask simple who/what/where questions, name familiar actions, and be understood by others some of the time. Clarity, language mix, and sentence length still vary widely.', 1),
(32, 'baby_development', 'any', 'any', null, 'Everyday thinking grows through daily play: matching or sorting by colour or size, enjoying number words, completing familiar routines, or copying simple lines and shapes may emerge. Keep it playful, not a skill to test.', 2),
(32, 'baby_development', 'any', 'any', null, 'Pretend play may become richer and more social - acting out small scenes, involving you or other children, and beginning to notice or join their play. This supports memory, language, imagination, and turn-taking.', 3),
(32, 'baby_development', 'any', 'any', null, 'For children born significantly premature, ask your paediatrician how to interpret development for them. Raise any loss of skills, a specific concern, or a question about communication or development promptly.', 4),
(32, 'mum_wellbeing', 'any', 'any', null, 'Big feelings continue through this stretch - the same rhythm helps: name the feeling, hold a short calm limit, offer two safe choices, reconnect once calm returns, and praise small moments of cooperation.', 0),
(32, 'mum_wellbeing', 'any', 'any', null, 'Seek support from your doctor or a trusted person if low mood, anxiety, anger, hopelessness, sleep trouble beyond toddler-related waking, or feeling unable to cope is lasting or worsening. Urgent help is needed if you feel unsafe or have thoughts of harming yourself or someone else.', 1),
(32, 'mum_wellbeing', 'any', 'any', null, 'Rest, shared care, and small moments for yourself remain valid priorities. A short walk, stretch, or quiet break can count; asking for help is part of caring for your family, not a failure to manage.', 2),
(32, 'buy_now', 'any', 'any', null, 'Offer 3-4 varied family meals and 1-2 nutritious snacks according to appetite. Include iron-rich foods such as dals/beans, eggs, meat/fish where eaten, and leafy vegetables; offer water with and between meals; and continue breastfeeding if you both wish. Cow''s milk or dairy can be part of the diet, but should not crowd out meals. Encourage, but do not force, eating.', 0),
(32, 'buy_now', 'any', 'any', null, 'Everyday materials support learning without special purchases: books, crayons, blocks, large-piece puzzles, and safe pretend props such as plastic cups, spoons, or scarves. Talk about colours, actions, and numbers during daily routines; avoid small detachable parts, sharp edges, batteries, and unsafe cupboards or rooms.', 1),
(32, 'buy_now', 'any', 'any', null, 'Lightweight summer clothing, a sun hat, and shade planning are worth arranging as outdoor time increases.', 2),
(32, 'hold_off', 'any', 'any', null, 'Keep food and household-safety boundaries: cut grapes lengthways into quarters; serve nuts crushed/ground or as smooth paste; avoid popcorn, hard sweets, and hard raw pieces; and keep eating seated and supervised. Lock button batteries, magnets, medicines, cleaners, and small objects away. If screens are used, keep them to no more than one hour a day of child content with an adult present, away from meals and bedtime. Follow toilet-training readiness gently, with no pressure around speech clarity, counting, or skill timing.', 0),
(32, 'movement_rest', 'any', 'any', null, 'Continue safe active play - running, jumping, climbing, ball play, and supervised stairs. Secure furniture, TVs, windows/balconies, and stairs; keep loose mats, cords, and small objects out of busy walking routes; and avoid seated wheeled walkers.', 0),
(32, 'movement_rest', 'any', 'any', null, 'Simple sorting, picture talk, counting games, and pretend scenes support thinking and language naturally. Let toddler try small self-help tasks with time and close supervision rather than turning play into a test.', 1),
(32, 'appointments_safety', 'any', 'any', null, 'If your child is up to date, no routine UIP vaccine dose is scheduled this month. Vitamin A continues every six months from 16-18 months until age five; confirm the card and next due date with your paediatrician or local programme, as private schedules and local services may differ. At the next planned health visit, share any developmental concern or a missed 30-month review, and ask whether formal screening would be useful or available.', 0),
(32, 'appointments_safety', 'any', 'any', null, 'If your toddler tries to climb out of the cot, plan a safe sleep arrangement rather than waiting for a fall: follow the cot maker''s guidance, consider a low age-appropriate bed when needed, toddler-proof the room, and gate stairs if needed. Use a correctly fitted child car restraint on every journey. Brush teeth twice daily with a rice-grain smear of fluoride toothpaste and arrange a dental visit if one has not yet happened or if you have concerns.', 1),
(32, 'appointments_safety', 'any', 'any', null, 'Seek urgent care for breathing difficulty, a seizure, unusual difficulty waking, a serious injury, suspected poisoning, or choking. Contact your paediatrician promptly for poor drinking or dehydration, repeated vomiting or diarrhoea, blood in stool, fever that worries you, or a child who seems much less alert than usual.', 2),
(32, 'appointments_safety', 'any', 'summer', null, 'A fast, bold toddler outdoors in summer heat needs frequent water, not just at meals, as well as shade, a sun hat, sunscreen used as directed, and outdoor play in the coolest practical hours. Offer freshly prepared food, refrigerate promptly, and discard food left out in the heat.', 3),
(32, 'appointments_safety', 'any', 'summer', null, 'Water safety stays paramount - focused, within-arm''s-reach adult supervision around any water; empty containers after use; block unsupervised pool and bathroom access; and never rely on inflatables or older children.', 4),
(32, 'appointments_safety', 'any', 'summer', null, 'Hot surfaces such as playground metal, pavement, and dark seats can burn quickly - check before contact. Use age-appropriate mosquito protection only as directed, and reduce standing water.', 5),
(32, 'appointments_safety', 'any', 'summer', null, 'Never leave your toddler in a parked vehicle, even briefly - temperatures rise dangerously fast, even with windows cracked.', 6),
(33, 'baby_development', 'any', 'any', null, 'Physical skills keep refining - a toddler may start walking up stairs with alternating feet, pedalling a tricycle, or trying to catch a large ball. Wide variation remains normal, so follow toddler''s lead and keep close supervision around steps, play equipment, and roads.', 0),
(33, 'baby_development', 'any', 'any', null, 'Language often expands - some toddlers hold short back-and-forth conversations, use action words, ask simple who/what/where questions, and are understood by others more of the time. Clarity, sentence length, and language mix still vary widely.', 1),
(33, 'baby_development', 'any', 'any', null, 'Everyday thinking grows through play: sorting, matching, counting games, noticing same/different, or copying simple lines and shapes may emerge. Keep it playful, not a skill to test.', 2),
(33, 'baby_development', 'any', 'any', null, 'Pretend play may grow more detailed and cooperative - playing out familiar scenes with you or other children, sometimes with simple roles and beginning to notice or join their play.', 3),
(33, 'baby_development', 'any', 'any', null, 'For children born significantly premature, ask your paediatrician how to interpret development for them. Raise any loss of skills, a specific concern, or a question about communication or development promptly.', 4),
(33, 'mum_wellbeing', 'any', 'any', null, 'Big feelings continue through this stretch - the same rhythm helps: name the feeling, hold a short calm limit, offer two safe choices, reconnect once calm returns, and praise small moments of cooperation.', 0),
(33, 'mum_wellbeing', 'any', 'any', null, 'Seek support from your doctor or a trusted person if low mood, anxiety, anger, hopelessness, sleep trouble beyond toddler-related waking, or feeling unable to cope is lasting or worsening. Urgent help is needed if you feel unsafe or have thoughts of harming yourself or someone else.', 1),
(33, 'mum_wellbeing', 'any', 'any', null, 'Rest, shared care, and small moments for yourself remain valid priorities. A short walk, stretch, or quiet break can count; asking for help is part of caring for your family, not a failure to manage.', 2),
